𝐄𝐯𝐢𝐝𝐞𝐧𝐜𝐞 𝐨𝐫 𝐄𝐱𝐢𝐭: 𝐒𝐞𝐧𝐚𝐭𝐨𝐫 𝐍𝐚𝐭𝐚𝐬𝐡𝐚 𝐀𝐤𝐩𝐨𝐭𝐢-𝐔𝐝𝐮𝐚𝐠𝐡𝐚𝐧 𝐌𝐮𝐬𝐭 𝐂𝐡𝐨𝐨𝐬𝐞

Senator @NatashaAkpoti’s latest Facebook post dismissing Dr. Sandra Duru’s (aka Prof. Mgbeke) May 1 live broadcast as “manipulated” and “politically motivated” offers no facts, no forensics, and certainly no credibility. What it does offer, unfortunately, is a continuation of a now familiar pattern: sensational allegations, quickly recycled into conspiracy claims once confronted with inconvenient evidence.

Dr. Duru’s two-hour livestream—complete with audio recordings and screenshots—directly contradicted the Senator’s repeated denials. These materials, if authentic, expose a troubling consistency: a public official weaponizing unproven accusations for political mileage, then falling back on deflection once the narrative begins to unravel.

To date, Senator Akpoti-Uduaghan has claimed, without presenting a single verifiable document, that:

1. Senate President Godswill Akpabio sexually harassed her;

2. Former Governor Yahaya Bello was contracted by Akpabio to assassinate her;

3. The Akpabios were involved in the 2021 death of a minor;

4. Her reassignment in the Senate seating plan was punishment for rejecting advances;

5. Her motions and bills are being blocked on the Senate floor;

6. She has been denied official travel approvals and now self-sponsors her statutory assignments;

7. And now, most recently, that all incriminating recordings are part of a grand “Akpabio script” read aloud by a woman she insists is a fraud.

Not one of these claims has been backed by a police report, a sworn affidavit, a Senate motion, or even a single authenticated document. And when confronted with contradictory evidence, the Senator’s response has been reflexive: attack the source, dismiss the proof, shift the narrative.

Let it be said plainly—Nigeria’s public institutions are not theatres for trial-by-sentiment. When elected leaders make explosive allegations, they owe the public something more than emotive storytelling. They owe facts.

At this point, four basic, non-negotiable steps remain:

1. Authenticate or refute Dr. Duru’s recordings through an independent forensic lab—publicly, not via hashtags or captions.

2. Present the evidence—police reports, court filings, Senate records, audio verifications—that support your claims.

3. If you believe you’ve been defamed, file suit. Nigeria has courts, not just cameras.

4. Failing the above, tender a public apology and resign honorably.

The integrity of Nigeria’s democratic institutions depends on the honesty and accountability of those who serve within them. In the interest of promoting accountability and restoring confidence in our national discourse, it is long overdue for Senator Natasha Akpoti-Uduaghan to stop hiding behind rhetoric and start supplying proof.

Nigerians deserve better than conjecture and drama. The time for storytelling has expired. The burden is now hers: evidence or exit.
